{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.17,0.23,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4127"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103619"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4127"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86036"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"6202"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5115"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5168"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42613"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103619"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a six-month history of central chest pain on exertion with associated shortness of breath and diaphoresis. Episodes last between one and three minutes and are alleviated by rest. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears well. His blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg. Laboratory investigations show hyperlipidaemia, and no ST changes are detected on ECG. He is prescribed a glyceryl trinitrate spray for acute relief, and atenolol 50mg nocte.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medication is the most appropriate second anti-anginal medication in this circumstance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nicorandil","Carvedilol","Verapamil","Amlodipine","Diltiazem"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmlodipine\u003C/strong\u003E is a dihydropyridine\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ecalcium channel blocker (such as amlodipine, modified-release nifedipine) can be added to a beta blocker as a second antianginal agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003Ediltiazem\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Everapamil\u003C/strong\u003E are non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers; they can cause severe bradycardia and heart failure when used in combination with beta-blockers. Due to this risk, neither should be used without cardiology input, nor are they routinely prescribed even by cardiologists. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarvedilol\u003C/strong\u003E, as a beta blocker, should not be added as a second-line agent. Prescribing two beta blockers may lead to severe bradycardia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Enicorandil, \u003C/strong\u003Ea potassium channel activator, can be used as an anti-anginal therapy, it is a third-line agent and should be considered for patients with refractory angina despite optimal standard therapy (i.e. after both a beta blocker and calcium channel blocker or nitrate has been trialled). \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta blockers and dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers are an effective antianginal combination.","When combined with non-dihydropyridines, beta blockers may lead to severe bradycardia."],"references":["Stable angina. In: Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Updated June 2023. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Belsey J, Savelieva I, Mugelli A, Camm AJ. Relative efficacy of antianginal drugs used as add-on therapy in patients with stable angina: A systematic review and meta-analysis. Eur J Prev Cardiol. 2015;22(7):837\u201348. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24776376/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86036"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11496"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86036"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T20:44:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T20:44:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4127"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103619"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},